   =20
      Carbon offsets
   =20
 =20

There are, I think, three main ways to get into the business of   selling c=
arbon offsets:
=09You are=C2=A0an environmentalist: You want to avert climate change, and =
you think that the carbon offsets business is a good way to do it. Your mot=
ives are essentially idealistic.=09You are   a logger: You own some timberl=
and, you cut it down to make lumber or paper, you track the markets for lum=
ber and paper closely, and you realize that the carbon offsets market will =
pay you more for=C2=A0not=C2=A0cutting down trees than the lumber market wi=
ll pay you for cutting them down. Your motives are straightforward and pric=
e-based.=09You are a financial engineer: You are in the business of structu=
ring financial products to address the perceived problems of people on both=
 sides of the trade, and sitting in the middle and taking a cut. Your compe=
titive position depends on coming up with creative new trades to propose, a=
nd creative new ways to take your cut. Carbon credits =E2=80=94=C2=A0which =
involve new and complicated accounting regimes, and which involve selling a=
 product that you=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0create (emissions) to people who =
don=E2=80=99t use it =E2=80=94=C2=A0are a particularly appealing generator =
of financial engineering. Your motives are basically profit-oriented, thoug=
h also somewhat aesthetic.=C2=A0

=E2=80=9CESG Consultant But Evil," I have   sometimes called the last categ=
ory.
There has been a=C2=A0lot of reporting, over the years, about how a lot of =
carbon offset projects are somewhat fake. In particular, a classic form of =
carbon credits comes from designating some forest and promising not to cut =
down the trees in that forest. That naturally leads to dubious accounting r=
egimes: The cheapest way to generate those credits is by promising not to c=
ut down trees that you wouldn=E2=80=99t have cut down anyway. And so there =
are verification and auditing regimes that are basically about figuring out=
 the baseline and making sure that people only get credits for not chopping=
 down trees that would otherwise have been chopped down. But this is imperf=
ect and game-able in various ways.
If you run a carbon credits business, and it comes to your attention that s=
ome of the credits that you are selling are fake =E2=80=94=C2=A0that you ar=
e getting paid for not chopping down trees that would not have been chopped=
 down anyway =E2=80=94=C2=A0what do you do about it? I think it sort of dep=
ends on your original motivations:
=09If you came to carbon credits as an environmentalist, then you will take=
 this news badly. You might announce your findings, apologize, pay back the=
 money and promise to do better. You might resign in a huff. Or you might n=
ot. You might have=C2=A0come=C2=A0to the business as an environmentalist, b=
ut it=E2=80=99s a good business. You might have gotten used to the money. Y=
ou might say =E2=80=9Cehh it=E2=80=99s good enough.=E2=80=9D Or =E2=80=9Cye=
s but we are making the world better by selling these credits, even if some=
 of them are fake, and let=E2=80=99s not undermine that by admitting to the=
 fakes.=E2=80=9D Your original idealistic principles might be compromised b=
y contact with the real world, or with money.=09If you came to carbon credi=
ts as a logger, you are just selling your trees to the highest bidder. You =
don=E2=80=99t care if it=E2=80=99s for fake carbon credits or real carbon c=
redits or pulp. This is a non-event.=09If you came to carbon credits as a f=
inancial engineer, and you find out that you are getting paid for some pure=
 accounting abstraction rather than for saving the world, you will be like =
=E2=80=9Cyes, exactly.=E2=80=9D If you are an ESG Consultant But Evil, the =
evil is part of the point.

At the New Yorker, Heidi Blake=C2=A0has a wild story about a carbon credit =
project in Zimbabwe. =E2=80=9CThe world=E2=80=99s largest carbon-offsetting=
 firm, South Pole Holding AG,=E2=80=9D structured =E2=80=9Ca deal to sell c=
arbon offsets from an effort to protect a vast swath of forest on the banks=
 of Lake Kariba.=E2=80=9D South Pole signed the deal with the owner of the =
forest, Steve Wentzel, =E2=80=9Ca former show jumper who had made a fortune=
 in offshore finance and then started investing in gold mines.=E2=80=9D Sou=
th Pole would sell the carbon credits to big companies that wanted to boast=
 that they were carbon neutral; it would take a cut and send the rest of th=
e money to Wentzel; he would take a cut and spend the rest of the money on=
=C2=A0projects (=E2=80=9Cfarming activities, =E2=80=A6 new school huts and =
clinics, anti-poaching patrols, and fire-suppression measures=E2=80=9D) to =
encourage local development without deforestation.
The thrust of the story is that (1) the money kind of disappeared and (2) a=
 lot of the carbon credits turned out to be fake.=C2=A0But I also enjoyed t=
he differing motives of the players.=C2=A0Renat Heuberger, the chief execut=
ive officer of South Pole, is portrayed as someone who got into carbon cred=
its because he was=C2=A0a committed environmentalist who wanted to change t=
he world, but who got used to the way things are done. By the time he was=
=C2=A0confronted with the carbon credits being fake, he didn=E2=80=99t care=
:
To Heuberger=E2=80=99s mind, the Kariba project was as good as it needed to=
 be: =E2=80=9CIs it perfect? Is the guy a hundred per cent? Every dollar al=
ways a hundred per cent?=E2=80=9D He shrugged. =E2=80=9CYou have to navigat=
e your way around.=E2=80=9D
This is a contrast to South Pole=E2=80=99s=C2=A0previous=C2=A0CEO, who deci=
ded that carbon credits were fake and quit:
=E2=80=9CI was building up this worry,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=
=99s just paper credits.=E2=80=9D He told me that he remained friends with =
Heuberger, but did not share his encompassing faith in offsetting. =E2=80=
=9CThe big majority of what you see in the market, in my view, boils down t=
o a lot of greenwashing, a lot of marketing, a lot of money-making,=E2=80=
=9D he said.=C2=A0
Meanwhile Dirk Muench, Heuberger's friend from college, had gone off to be =
an investment banker, got disillusioned and joined South Pole. He=C2=A0was=
=C2=A0a financial engineer, but he got into the carbon credits racket as an=
 idealist, and he seems to have stayed one: He got a bad feeling about the =
Kariba project, investigated it, decided that the money was misplaced and t=
he credits fake, and made trouble:
On July 9th, Muench sent an e-mail to Heuberger and other executives, with =
the subject line =E2=80=9CRed Flag.=E2=80=9D He reported that, after a long=
 investigation, he could only conclude that most of the funds for the Karib=
a project had gone astray. In private, he says, he urged Heuberger to admit=
 the problems: =E2=80=9CWe need to come public before it is in the press.=
=E2=80=9D
And was ignored:
Heuberger was disinclined to listen to Muench. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s very d=
riven=E2=80=94the mind-set is totally on impact,=E2=80=9D Heuberger told me=
. =E2=80=9CFor him, there=E2=80=99s only good and bad.=E2=80=9D South Pole =
removed Muench from the inquiry into Wentzel=E2=80=99s finances, after whic=
h =E2=80=9Cthe relationship and flow of information proved to be more produ=
ctive again,=E2=80=9D the company said
And then there is Wentzel, =E2=80=9Ca white Zimbabwean tycoon,=E2=80=9D who=
 doesn=E2=80=99t care about any of this, got the Kariba land =E2=80=9Cas pa=
yment for a debt,=E2=80=9D and is a fountain of gleefully cynical quotes:
=E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t know anything,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=
=99m not a tree scientist or anything like that.=E2=80=9D
And, sure, he took a lot of money from South Pole without being able to acc=
ount for how it was spent, but, see, that was on purpose:=C2=A0

Years of political and economic instability had made it too precarious to b=
ank in Zimbabwe, he said, and transferring money to a sanctioned state from=
 Guernsey was a bureaucratic headache: =E2=80=9CDo you know how much compli=
ance I had to go through to just have one transaction?=E2=80=9D So he had d=
evised an untraceable way of moving the funds. =E2=80=9CIt was illegal,=E2=
=80=9D he acknowledged, =E2=80=9Cbut it got looked over.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=
=80=A6
=E2=80=9CThis looks really bad, because you=E2=80=99re just sending money h=
ere, there, and everywhere, but, on the receiving side, I can show where we=
=E2=80=99ve got it,=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=9CWell, I can show you the =
bundles of cash on the floor.=E2=80=9D When payments arrived, he said, he w=
ould =E2=80=9Cgrab the money and run with it,=E2=80=9D distributing it amon=
g the stakeholders in the project. =E2=80=9CFor any kind of European or Ame=
rican, that=E2=80=99s not comprehensible,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CHow ma=
ny Western people have carried half a million dollars of cash in their hand=
?=E2=80=9D
Wentzel=E2=80=99s demeanor seemed to lighten as he unburdened himself, and =
he began to stage a mock interrogation. =E2=80=9CCan I see the=C2=A0swift?=
=E2=80=9D he boomed, referring to the code that banks use for international=
 payments. =E2=80=9CThe money got there swiftly, but I can=E2=80=99t tell y=
ou what the=C2=A0swift=C2=A0was.=E2=80=9D Suddenly his waggish smile gave w=
ay to a frown. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t know what you=E2=80=99re going to r=
eport on this, and I hope to God it=E2=80=99s not all of it, because I prob=
ably will go to jail,=E2=80=9D he said. Then he reassured himself. =E2=80=
=9CI=E2=80=99ll go to jail for the right reasons,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=
=9CSavior or villain? I=E2=80=99m right in the damned middle. And I=E2=80=
=99m happy to be that way.=E2=80=9D

I sometimes talk around here about not putting compromising things in email=
, but if you are going around telling a New Yorker=C2=A0reporter, on the re=
cord, =E2=80=9CI=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t know what you=E2=80=99re going to repor=
t on this, and I hope to God it=E2=80=99s not all of it, because I probably=
 will go to jail,=E2=80=9D you are far beyond my power to help or harm you.=
 I bet that guy will be fine. Also: =E2=80=9CA hundred thousand dollars is =
only as big as a brick,=E2=80=9D he tells Blake. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not =
difficult to carry it around.=E2=80=9D
Anyway that=E2=80=99s the money. The bigger problem at Kariba, arguably, is=
 that some of the carbon credits were fake. What that means specifically is=
 that the project was registered with Verra, a nonprofit that serves as=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9Cthe primary standard-setter of the voluntary carbon trade,=E2=
=80=9D which has a methodology to determine if a project is actually preser=
ving trees:
To register the Kariba project with Verra, South Pole had to predict how mu=
ch of the forest would be lost without any intervention, and thus determine=
 how much carbon the scheme would conserve over a thirty-year life span. Cr=
edits would be issued every year against that total, and the prediction wou=
ld be checked once a decade, by comparing Kariba with an unguarded referenc=
e area nearby. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0On that basis, the project would be eligible =
for almost two hundred million credits.
And so they went out and sold lots of=C2=A0credits. But then when they chec=
ked, years later, they found that they had sold too many, because Kariba ha=
d not had nearly the effects they had calculated, in part because it lost s=
ome trees but mostly because the reference forest did not:
Project monitors had surveyed the site and found fewer trees than South Pol=
e planned to claim credit for. Then [South Pole co-founder Christian] Danne=
cker learned something even more alarming: the rate of forest loss in the p=
roject=E2=80=99s reference region=E2=80=94the benchmark against which its s=
uccess would be measured=E2=80=94was starkly lower than projected. The wave=
 of deforestation that South Pole=E2=80=99s efforts were supposed to preven=
t was looking more like a trickle, which could significantly diminish the v=
alue of the project.
The problem with this anti-deforestation project was that there was=C2=A0to=
o little deforestation. That seems good? For the climate? But bad for the p=
eople hawking carbon credits. The idealistic Muench pointed out the problem=
, and the now-jaded Heuberger was like =E2=80=9Cmeh still fine=E2=80=9D:
Muench and another executive urged Heuberger to stop selling offsets from t=
he Kariba project immediately. =E2=80=9CIf it comes out that we=E2=80=99ve =
knowingly sold credits that weren=E2=80=99t equivalent to a ton of CO2=C2=
=A0emissions avoided, it would do huge damage,=E2=80=9D Muench said. Heuber=
ger rejected that idea. The credits had been validated by Verra, he argued:=
 =E2=80=9CIf you want to scale, you have to rely on certain rules and syste=
ms.=E2=80=9D
And there was a staff meeting that really got to the heart of the problem:

=E2=80=9CAre the Kariba credits based on reality?=E2=80=9D one staffer aske=
d.
=E2=80=9CI give the question back: What is reality?=E2=80=9D Dannecker snap=
ped.
South Pole=E2=80=99s head of U.S. sales tried again: =E2=80=9CWe have clien=
ts coming to us saying, =E2=80=98Hey, the credits that you sold us, that im=
pact that we claimed, did that actually happen? Yes or no?=E2=80=99=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9D
A public-affairs executive intervened: =E2=80=9CWhich is why we=E2=80=99re =
holding the current verification at the moment=E2=80=94because we want to m=
ake sure that that is the case.=E2=80=9D
=E2=80=9CHow much profit has South Pole made by selling Kariba credits?=E2=
=80=9D another staffer asked.
=E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=99t do the numbers, to be honest,=E2=80=9D Dannecker =
replied. =E2=80=9CI guess we probably made ten million dollars.=E2=80=9D Th=
ere were audible gasps, before another executive warned, =E2=80=9CTo be cle=
ar, we don=E2=80=99t want to repeat that publicly.=E2=80=9D

I hesitate to point it out, but I am a financial engineer at heart, and=C2=
=A0there is a solution here. The essential problem with Kariba is not that =
the trees in the protected forest were cut down: They mostly weren=E2=80=99=
t. The problem is that the trees in the unprotected reference=C2=A0forest=
=C2=A0also weren=E2=80=99t cut down. Simply speaking, the carbon impact of =
the Kariba project is calculated by (1) adding up the trees in Kariba that =
were not cut down and (2) subtracting the trees in the reference forest tha=
t were not cut down. If Kariba was perfectly preserved and the reference fo=
rest was razed to the ground, then Kariba did a good job of protecting tree=
s in a dangerous neighborhood for trees. If Kariba was perfectly preserved =
and the reference forest was=C2=A0also=C2=A0perfectly preserved, then Karib=
a had no real effect on emissions.
You see the solution, right? The solution is: You are a shady guy anyway, y=
ou do lots of stuff off the books, you have access to a poorly paid local w=
orkforce who want to continue getting the economic benefits of the carbon c=
redit project,=C2=A0you hand them a brick of cash to burn down the referenc=
e forest.
More generally the optimal way to do carbon offsets is:
=09You set up an entity called like Green Niceness that buys a forest and p=
romises to preserve it.=09You have your buddy set up an entity called Nasty=
 Lumber LLC, with no traceable ties to you or Green Niceness, that buys a n=
earby forest.=09You get Green Niceness=E2=80=99s forest certified as a carb=
on offset project, with Nasty Lumber=E2=80=99s forest as the reference fore=
st.=09Green Niceness puts a fence around its trees; Nasty Lumber deforests =
as fast as it can.=09Green Niceness makes a lot of money selling carbon cre=
dits; Nasty Lumber probably makes some money selling lumber.=09You split th=
e profits by passing around=C2=A0bricks of cash.

I mean, not optimal for the world or anything, just optimal for you.=C2=A0

