<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are, I think, three main ways to get int=
o the business of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
33057398.256428/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzI=
wMjEtMDQtMjEveW91LWNhbi1zZWxsLXRoZS10cmVlcy15b3UtZG9uLXQtY3V0P2NtcGlkPUJCRD=
EwMTcyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJ=
nV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMTAxNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cBa14147ed" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">  selling carbon offsets</a>:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You are=C2=A0an environmentalist: You=
 want to avert climate change, and you think that the carbon offsets busine=
ss is a good way to do it. Your motives are essentially idealistic.</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/33057398.256428/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMTgvcHVycGxlLWR1bXBzLWl0cy1wcnBscz9jbXBpZD=
1CQkQxMDE3MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xld=
HRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEwMTcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB491a6f29" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">  a logger</a>: You own some timberland, you cut=
 it down to make lumber or paper, you track the markets for lumber and pape=
r closely, and you realize that the carbon offsets market will pay you more=
 for=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>cutting down trees than the lumber market will =
pay you for cutting them down. Your motives are straightforward and price-b=
ased.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You are a financial engineer=
: You are in the business of structuring financial products to address the =
perceived problems of people on both sides of the trade, and sitting in the=
 middle and taking a cut. Your competitive position depends on coming up wi=
th creative new trades to propose, and creative new ways to take your cut. =
Carbon credits =E2=80=94=C2=A0which involve new and complicated accounting =
regimes, and which involve selling a product that you=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0create (emissions) to people who don=E2=80=99t use it =E2=80=94=C2=A0are=
 a particularly appealing generator of financial engineering. Your motives =
are basically profit-oriented, though also somewhat aesthetic.=C2=A0</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CESG Consultant But Evil," I have <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33057398.256428/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTUvbWF0dC1sZ=
XZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1iaW5hbmNlLWZ0eC1hbmQtY2Fycz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDE3MjNf=
TU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGV=
ybT0yMzEwMTcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1d4ab=
c03" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  sometimes called</a> the last category.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There has been a=C2=A0<em>lot</em> of reportin=
g, over the years, about how a lot of carbon offset projects are somewhat f=
ake. In particular, a classic form of carbon credits comes from designating=
 some forest and promising not to cut down the trees in that forest. That n=
aturally leads to dubious accounting regimes: The cheapest way to generate =
those credits is by promising not to cut down trees that you wouldn=E2=80=
=99t have cut down anyway. And so there are verification and auditing regim=
es that are basically about figuring out the baseline and making sure that =
people only get credits for not chopping down trees that would otherwise ha=
ve been chopped down. But this is imperfect and game-able in various ways.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you run a carbon credits business, and it c=
omes to your attention that some of the credits that you are selling are fa=
ke =E2=80=94=C2=A0that you are getting paid for not chopping down trees tha=
t would not have been chopped down anyway =E2=80=94=C2=A0what do you do abo=
ut it? I think it sort of depends on your original motivations:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you came to carbon credits as an e=
nvironmentalist, then you will take this news badly. You might announce you=
r findings, apologize, pay back the money and promise to do better. You mig=
ht resign in a huff. Or you might not. You might have=C2=A0<em>come=C2=A0</=
em>to the business as an environmentalist, but it=E2=80=99s a good business=
. You might have gotten used to the money. You might say =E2=80=9Cehh it=E2=
=80=99s good enough.=E2=80=9D Or =E2=80=9Cyes but we are making the world b=
etter by selling these credits, even if some of them are fake, and let=E2=
=80=99s not undermine that by admitting to the fakes.=E2=80=9D Your origina=
l idealistic principles might be compromised by contact with the real world=
, or with money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you came to ca=
rbon credits as a logger, you are just selling your trees to the highest bi=
dder. You don=E2=80=99t care if it=E2=80=99s for fake carbon credits or rea=
l carbon credits or pulp. This is a non-event.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">If you came to carbon credits as a financial engineer, and you=
 find out that you are getting paid for some pure accounting abstraction ra=
ther than for saving the world, you will be like =E2=80=9Cyes, exactly.=E2=
=80=9D If you are an ESG Consultant But Evil, the evil is part of the point=
.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the New Yorker, Heidi Blake=C2=A0<a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33057398.256428/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cubmV3eW9ya2VyLmNvbS9tYWdhemluZS8yMDIzLzEwLzIzL3RoZS1ncmVhdC1jYXNoLWZvci1=
jYXJib24taHVzdGxl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3a3ca12f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">has a wild sto=
ry about a carbon credit project in Zimbabwe</a>. =E2=80=9CThe world=E2=80=
=99s largest carbon-offsetting firm, South Pole Holding AG,=E2=80=9D struct=
ured =E2=80=9Ca deal to sell carbon offsets from an effort to protect a vas=
t swath of forest on the banks of Lake Kariba.=E2=80=9D South Pole signed t=
he deal with the owner of the forest, Steve Wentzel, =E2=80=9Ca former show=
 jumper who had made a fortune in offshore finance and then started investi=
ng in gold mines.=E2=80=9D South Pole would sell the carbon credits to big =
companies that wanted to boast that they were carbon neutral; it would take=
 a cut and send the rest of the money to Wentzel; he would take a cut and s=
pend the rest of the money on=C2=A0projects (=E2=80=9Cfarming activities, =
=E2=80=A6 new school huts and clinics, anti-poaching patrols, and fire-supp=
ression measures=E2=80=9D) to encourage local development without deforesta=
tion.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The thrust of the story is that (1) the money =
kind of disappeared and (2) a lot of the carbon credits turned out to be fa=
ke.=C2=A0But I also enjoyed the differing motives of the players.=C2=A0Rena=
t Heuberger, the chief executive officer of South Pole, is portrayed as som=
eone who got into carbon credits because he was=C2=A0a committed environmen=
talist who wanted to change the world, but who got used to the way things a=
re done. By the time he was=C2=A0confronted with the carbon credits being f=
ake, he didn=E2=80=99t care:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To Heuberger=E2=80=99s mind, the K=
ariba project was as good as it needed to be: =E2=80=9CIs it perfect? Is th=
e guy a hundred per cent? Every dollar always a hundred per cent?=E2=80=9D =
He shrugged. =E2=80=9CYou have to navigate your way around.=E2=80=9D</p></b=
lockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a contrast to South Pole=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0<em>previous=C2=A0</em>CEO, who decided that carbon credits were fake an=
d quit:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI was building up this wo=
rry,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s just paper credits.=E2=80=9D H=
e told me that he remained friends with Heuberger, but did not share his en=
compassing faith in offsetting. =E2=80=9CThe big majority of what you see i=
n the market, in my view, boils down to a lot of greenwashing, a lot of mar=
keting, a lot of money-making,=E2=80=9D he said.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile Dirk Muench, Heuberger's friend from=
 college, had gone off to be an investment banker, got disillusioned and jo=
ined South Pole. He=C2=A0<em>was=C2=A0</em>a financial engineer, but he got=
 into the carbon credits racket as an idealist, and he seems to have stayed=
 one: He got a bad feeling about the Kariba project, investigated it, decid=
ed that the money was misplaced and the credits fake, and made trouble:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On July 9th, Muench sent an e-mail=
 to Heuberger and other executives, with the subject line =E2=80=9CRed Flag=
.=E2=80=9D He reported that, after a long investigation, he could only conc=
lude that most of the funds for the Kariba project had gone astray. In priv=
ate, he says, he urged Heuberger to admit the problems: =E2=80=9CWe need to=
 come public before it is in the press.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And was ignored:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Heuberger was disinclined to liste=
n to Muench. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s very driven=E2=80=94the mind-set is tota=
lly on impact,=E2=80=9D Heuberger told me. =E2=80=9CFor him, there=E2=80=99=
s only good and bad.=E2=80=9D South Pole removed Muench from the inquiry in=
to Wentzel=E2=80=99s finances, after which =E2=80=9Cthe relationship and fl=
ow of information proved to be more productive again,=E2=80=9D the company =
said</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then there is Wentzel, =E2=80=9Ca white Zi=
mbabwean tycoon,=E2=80=9D who doesn=E2=80=99t care about any of this, got t=
he Kariba land =E2=80=9Cas payment for a debt,=E2=80=9D and is a fountain o=
f gleefully cynical quotes:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t know anyt=
hing,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m not a tree scientist or anythi=
ng like that.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And, sure, he took a lot of money from South P=
ole without being able to account for how it was spent, but, see, that was =
on purpose:=C2=A0</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Years of political and economic instability ha=
d made it too precarious to bank in Zimbabwe, he said, and transferring mon=
ey to a sanctioned state from Guernsey was a bureaucratic headache: =E2=80=
=9CDo you know how much compliance I had to go through to just have one tra=
nsaction?=E2=80=9D So he had devised an untraceable way of moving the funds=
. =E2=80=9CIt was illegal,=E2=80=9D he acknowledged, =E2=80=9Cbut it got lo=
oked over.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThis looks really bad, because you=E2=
=80=99re just sending money here, there, and everywhere, but, on the receiv=
ing side, I can show where we=E2=80=99ve got it,=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=
=80=9CWell, I can show you the bundles of cash on the floor.=E2=80=9D When =
payments arrived, he said, he would =E2=80=9Cgrab the money and run with it=
,=E2=80=9D distributing it among the stakeholders in the project. =E2=80=9C=
For any kind of European or American, that=E2=80=99s not comprehensible,=E2=
=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CHow many Western people have carried half a millio=
n dollars of cash in their hand?=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wentzel=E2=80=99s demeanor seemed to lighten a=
s he unburdened himself, and he began to stage a mock interrogation. =E2=80=
=9CCan I see the=C2=A0<em>swift</em>?=E2=80=9D he boomed, referring to the =
code that banks use for international payments. =E2=80=9CThe money got ther=
e swiftly, but I can=E2=80=99t tell you what the=C2=A0<em>swift</em>=C2=A0w=
as.=E2=80=9D Suddenly his waggish smile gave way to a frown. =E2=80=9CI don=
=E2=80=99t know what you=E2=80=99re going to report on this, and I hope to =
God it=E2=80=99s not all of it, because I probably will go to jail,=E2=80=
=9D he said. Then he reassured himself. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll go to jail fo=
r the right reasons,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CSavior or villain? I=E2=80=
=99m right in the damned middle. And I=E2=80=99m happy to be that way.=E2=
=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I sometimes talk around here about not putting=
 compromising things in email, but if you are going around telling a New Yo=
rker=C2=A0reporter, on the record, =E2=80=9CI=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t know what =
you=E2=80=99re going to report on this, and I hope to God it=E2=80=99s not =
all of it, because I probably will go to jail,=E2=80=9D you are far beyond =
my power to help or harm you. I bet that guy will be fine. Also: =E2=80=9CA=
 hundred thousand dollars is only as big as a brick,=E2=80=9D he tells Blak=
e. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not difficult to carry it around.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway that=E2=80=99s the money. The bigger pr=
oblem at Kariba, arguably, is that some of the carbon credits were fake. Wh=
at that means specifically is that the project was registered with Verra, a=
 nonprofit that serves as=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe primary standard-setter of the =
voluntary carbon trade,=E2=80=9D which has a methodology to determine if a =
project is actually preserving trees:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To register the Kariba project wit=
h Verra, South Pole had to predict how much of the forest would be lost wit=
hout any intervention, and thus determine how much carbon the scheme would =
conserve over a thirty-year life span. Credits would be issued every year a=
gainst that total, and the prediction would be checked once a decade, by co=
mparing Kariba with an unguarded reference area nearby. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0On t=
hat basis, the project would be eligible for almost two hundred million cre=
dits.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so they went out and sold lots of=C2=A0cre=
dits. But then when they checked, years later, they found that they had sol=
d too many, because Kariba had not had nearly the effects they had calculat=
ed, in part because it lost some trees but mostly because the reference for=
est did not:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Project monitors had surveyed the =
site and found fewer trees than South Pole planned to claim credit for. The=
n [South Pole co-founder Christian] Dannecker learned something even more a=
larming: the rate of forest loss in the project=E2=80=99s reference region=
=E2=80=94the benchmark against which its success would be measured=E2=80=94=
was starkly lower than projected. The wave of deforestation that South Pole=
=E2=80=99s efforts were supposed to prevent was looking more like a trickle=
, which could significantly diminish the value of the project.</p></blockqu=
ote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The problem with this anti-deforestation proje=
ct was that there was=C2=A0<em>too little deforestation</em>. That seems go=
od? For the climate? But bad for the people hawking carbon credits. The ide=
alistic Muench pointed out the problem, and the now-jaded Heuberger was lik=
e =E2=80=9Cmeh still fine=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Muench and another executive urged=
 Heuberger to stop selling offsets from the Kariba project immediately. =E2=
=80=9CIf it comes out that we=E2=80=99ve knowingly sold credits that weren=
=E2=80=99t equivalent to a ton of CO2=C2=A0emissions avoided, it would do h=
uge damage,=E2=80=9D Muench said. Heuberger rejected that idea. The credits=
 had been validated by Verra, he argued: =E2=80=9CIf you want to scale, you=
 have to rely on certain rules and systems.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And there was a staff meeting that really got =
to the heart of the problem:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CAre the Kariba credits based on reali=
ty?=E2=80=9D one staffer asked.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI give the question back: What is rea=
lity?=E2=80=9D Dannecker snapped.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">South Pole=E2=80=99s head of U.S. sales tried =
again: =E2=80=9CWe have clients coming to us saying, =E2=80=98Hey, the cred=
its that you sold us, that impact that we claimed, did that actually happen=
? Yes or no?=E2=80=99=C2=A0=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A public-affairs executive intervened: =E2=80=
=9CWhich is why we=E2=80=99re holding the current verification at the momen=
t=E2=80=94because we want to make sure that that is the case.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CHow much profit has South Pole made b=
y selling Kariba credits?=E2=80=9D another staffer asked.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=99t do the numbers, to b=
e honest,=E2=80=9D Dannecker replied. =E2=80=9CI guess we probably made ten=
 million dollars.=E2=80=9D There were audible gasps, before another executi=
ve warned, =E2=80=9CTo be clear, we don=E2=80=99t want to repeat that publi=
cly.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I hesitate to point it out, but I am a financi=
al engineer at heart, and=C2=A0there <em>is</em> a solution here. The essen=
tial problem with Kariba is not that the trees in the protected forest were=
 cut down: They mostly weren=E2=80=99t. The problem is that the trees in th=
e unprotected reference=C2=A0forest=C2=A0<em>also </em>weren=E2=80=99t cut =
down. Simply speaking, the carbon impact of the Kariba project is calculate=
d by (1) adding up the trees in Kariba that were not cut down and (2) subtr=
acting the trees in the reference forest that were not cut down. If Kariba =
was perfectly preserved and the reference forest was razed to the ground, t=
hen Kariba did a good job of protecting trees in a dangerous neighborhood f=
or trees. If Kariba was perfectly preserved and the reference forest was=C2=
=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>perfectly preserved, then Kariba had no real effect o=
n emissions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You see the solution, right? The solution is: =
You are a shady guy anyway, you do lots of stuff off the books, you have ac=
cess to a poorly paid local workforce who want to continue getting the econ=
omic benefits of the carbon credit project,=C2=A0<em>you hand them a brick =
of cash to burn down the reference forest</em>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More generally the optimal way to do carbon of=
fsets is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You set up an entity called like Gree=
n Niceness that buys a forest and promises to preserve it.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have your buddy set up an entity called Nasty =
Lumber LLC, with no traceable ties to you or Green Niceness, that buys a ne=
arby forest.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You get Green Nicenes=
s=E2=80=99s forest certified as a carbon offset project, with Nasty Lumber=
=E2=80=99s forest as the reference forest.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">Green Niceness puts a fence around its trees; Nasty Lumber defores=
ts as fast as it can.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Green Nicene=
ss makes a lot of money selling carbon credits; Nasty Lumber probably makes=
 some money selling lumber.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You sp=
lit the profits by passing around=C2=A0bricks of cash.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean, not optimal for the world or anything,=
 just optimal for you.=C2=A0</p>
