c;">  wrote yesterday</a> about hypothetical abuses of investment bank meal=
 allowances. I proposed a few, and ended with =E2=80=9COr you do one of the=
 seven more creative minor abuses that my readers are going to email me abo=
ut today.=E2=80=9D Here are two. First:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I eat a big lunch, but not a huge =
dinner. So the $45 we get for dinner doesn't do much for me. What I do is g=
o to our local food court, buy my $15 salad, and then tip the guy the remai=
ning $30. The next day, when I'm getting lunch, the guy will conveniently "=
forget" to ring up half the items.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Principal/agent problems on=C2=A0<em>both=C2=
=A0</em>sides, love it. And:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At [one firm], it was very common =
for senior employees to have a waiter change the =E2=80=9Cnumber of guests=
=E2=80=9D that often appears on a receipt to, say, =E2=80=9C14 people=E2=80=
=9D and claim employees or clients were at dinner when it was really just 2=
 guys racking up a $2000 bar tab at a Tuesday.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s like =E2=80=A6=C2=A0kind of a m=
edium-level abuse?</p>
